{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659635"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20879"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96613"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13754"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79247"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"10764"},{"type":"tags","id":"11793"},{"type":"tags","id":"12702"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96613"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristics of autosomal recessive disorders?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uniform expression with early onset in life","Male-to-male transmission pattern","Higher frequency in males than females","Affected individuals in every generation","Worsening of symptoms in successive generations"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Euniform expression with early onset in life\u003C/strong\u003E. Autosomal recessive disorders typically show more uniform expression of the phenotype compared to dominant disorders, and they frequently manifest early in life. These disorders occur when both alleles at a given gene locus are mutated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey characteristics of autosomal recessive disorders include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EComplete penetrance is common\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EParents are typically unaffected carriers (heterozygotes)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESiblings have a 25% risk of inheriting the disorder\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMany involve enzyme deficiencies where heterozygotes function normally with half the enzyme complement\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMale-to-male transmission pattern\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a characteristic of autosomal dominant disorders, not recessive ones. Male-to-male transmission excludes X-linked inheritance.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigher frequency in males than females\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern suggests X-linked recessive inheritance; autosomal recessive disorders affect males and females equally.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAffected individuals in every generation\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern suggests autosomal dominant inheritance; recessive disorders typically skip generations.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWorsening of symptoms in successive generations\u003C/strong\u003E - This phenomenon, known as anticipation, is associated with trinucleotide repeat disorders like Huntington disease, not typical autosomal recessive conditions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn autosomal recessive disorders, both parents are typically heterozygous carriers who are phenotypically normal. The risk of having an affected child when both parents are carriers is 25% for each pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autosomal recessive disorders require mutations in both alleles at a given gene locus and represent the largest category of Mendelian disorders.","Autosomal recessive disorders typically show uniform expression, complete penetrance, and early onset in life.","Most autosomal recessive disorders involve enzyme deficiencies where heterozygotes function normally with half the enzyme complement.","New mutations in autosomal recessive disorders are rarely detected clinically as carriers are asymptomatic."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 145-146"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79247"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20879"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79247"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T12:01:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T12:02:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13754"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96613"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"d